http://restbrowser.bitbucket.org/ lists a method of POSTing to create a team via

{code}
https://bitbucket.org/api/1.0/users/{accountname}/privileges/{group_owner}/{group_slug}/
{code}

The https://confluence.atlassian.com/display/BITBUCKET/Version+2 docs suggest the team API is/will be accessed via POST to (similar to groups in 1.0):

{code}
https://bitbucket.org/api/2.0/teams/{teamname}
{code}

Currently, the former throws a Django traceback.

a) Which uri is/will be correct?

b) What is the ETA for this feature?

https://bitbucket.org/tlroche/lightningnox/raw/238e6f9c19aa1211bcff81fda1b45d3df7f75157/README.md and its predecessor https://bitbucket.org/tlroche/lightningnox/raw/eae1d18b45457c1166ac30f5434760fc376a68d0/README.md each define and use the link

{code}
[R @ wikipedia]: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/R_%28programming language%29
{code}

as well as very similar links, e.g.,

{code}
[bash @ wikipedia]: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bash_%28Unix_shell%29
{code}

The BB markdown renderer "does the right thing" with the latter definition--and every other link in the file!--but refuses to render the former. And unless I&#x27;m missing something, there&#x27;s nothing wrong with the former. Am I missing something?

Since today, every time I try to put a new internal link on my private wiki, or edit a page with existing internal links, this:

{code}
#!markdown

[[test]]
{code}

Comes out like this:

{code}
#!html

https://bitbucket.org/blah/blah/wiki/:pathtest

{code}

Which then of course does not link to the right article.
